'''Edson Omar Álvarez Velázquez''' ({{IPA|es|ˈedson ˈalβaɾes}}; born 24 October 1997) is a Mexican professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays either as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] or [[centre-back]] for {{Turkish football updater|Fenerbahçe}} club [[Fenerbahçe S.K. (football)|Fenerbahçe]], on loan from {{English football updater|WestHamU}} club [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], and [[Captain (association football)|captains]] the [[Mexico national football team|Mexico national team]].

==Early life==
Álvarez was born in [[Tlalnepantla de Baz]], a municipality just north of [[Mexico City]], to Adriana Velázquez and Evaristo Álvarez.<ref name="ESPN bio">{{cite web|title=Edson Álvarez, un águila de calle |date=4 November 2016 |url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/mexico/nota/_/id/2839745/edson-alvarez-un-aguila-de-calle |trans-title=Edson Álvarez, an eagle from the streets |publisher=ESPN Deportes |language=es |access-date=4 November 2016}}</ref> As a child he worked for his family's business of manufacturing football kits for local teams, which he cites as his first foray into the sport.<ref name="FT bio">{{cite web |title=Causa y Efecto de… Edson Álvarez |url=https://www.futboltotal.com.mx/2017/07/causa-efecto-edson-alvarez/ |trans-title=Cause and Effect of… Edson Álvarez |publisher=Futbol Total |language=es |access-date=2 July 2017 |archive-date=22 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822182122/https://www.futboltotal.com.mx/2017/07/causa-efecto-edson-alvarez/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> At the age of 10, Álvarez joined [[C.F. Pachuca|Pachuca]], before leaving the club just two years later due to his short stature.<ref name=" FT bio" /><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-04-09 |title=Edson Álvarez visita y motiva a la Sub-17 de Pachuca que juega torneo del Ajax en Ámsterdam |trans-title=Edson Álvarez visits and motivates the Pachuca U-17 team playing in the Ajax tournament in Amsterdam. |url=https://www.tudn.com/futbol/dutch-eredivisie/edson-alvarez-visita-motiva-sub-17-pachuca-que-juega-torneo-ajax-amsterdam |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=www.tudn.com |language=es}}</ref> Contemplating quitting football, to the resistance of his parents who believed he had the talent to pursue his dream of playing professionally, Álvarez decided to try out for [[Club América]]'s youth team, eventually making the team after a three-month tryout. He would make it to the daily team practices by way of a three-to-four-hour round trip commute from his home in Tlalnepantla and the club's [[Instalaciones Club América en Coapa|training ground]] in [[Coapa]]. According to Álvarez, he would spend almost 70 percent of his monthly salary toward transportation.<ref name="FT bio" />

==Club career==
===América===
In 2014, at age 16, Álvarez joined [[Club América]]'s youth system, playing for the under-17 team.<ref name="ESPN bio" /> The following year, while still playing for the under-17 squad, Álvarez was promoted to América's [[Segunda División de México|second division]] team.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Página Oficial de la Liga Mexicana del Fútbol Profesional |trans-title=Official Page of the Mexican Professional Football League |url=https://ligamx.net/cancha/jugador/102742/edson-omar-alvarez-velazquez |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230713023329/https://ligamx.net/cancha/jugador/102742/edson-omar-alvarez-velazquez |archive-date=2023-07-13 |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=ligamx.net |language=es-MX}}</ref>

In August 2016, first team coach [[Ignacio Ambríz]] gave Álvarez his first call-up, sitting on the bench in América's week 5 [[Liga MX|league]] match against [[Monarcas Morelia]], using the jersey number 282.<ref name="FT bio" /> On 29 October, newly appointed coach [[Ricardo La Volpe]] gave 19-year-old Álvarez his Liga MX debut in the team's win over [[Santos Laguna]]; he played all 90 minutes and was voted third in a ''Man of the Match'' online poll by club fans.<ref>{{cite web |title=Edson Álvarez debuta en la Liga MX |trans-title=Edson Álvarez debuts in the Liga MX |url=http://www.clubamerica.com.mx/comunicados/edson-alvarez-debuta-la-liga-mx/ |access-date=29 October 2016 |website=ClubAmérica.com.mx |publisher=Club América |language=es}}</ref> On 25 December, he scored his first career goal in the [[2016–17 Liga MX season#Torneo Apertura|Apertura]] final against [[Tigres UANL]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Video: Gol de Edson Álvarez contra Tigres |trans-title=Video: Goal by Edson Álvarez against Tigres |url=http://www.goal.com/es-mx/news/4774/liga-bancomer-mx/2016/12/25/30851422/video-el-gol-de-edson-%C3%A1lvarez-contra-tigres |access-date=25 December 2016 |work=Goal (website) |language=es}}</ref>

Prior to the start of the [[2017–18 Liga MX season|2017–18 season]], Álvarez was handed the number 4 shirt, which was vacated following the departure of [[Erik Pimentel]].<ref>{{cite web|title=América registra 11 jugadores de 21 años o menos |trans-title=America registers 11 players aged 21 and under |url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/mexico/nota/_/id/3386279/america-registra-11-jugadores-de-21-anos-o-menos |publisher=ESPN |language=es |date=12 July 2017 |access-date=12 July 2017}}</ref>

On 16 December 2018, Álvarez was given the start for the return leg of the [[2018–19 Liga MX season#Torneo Apertura|Apertura final]] against [[Cruz Azul]], playing in midfield in place of the injured [[Mateus Uribe]], and scored twice as América won its 13th league title following a 2–0 aggregate score.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hernandez |first=Cesar |date=2018-12-19 |title=Edson Alvarez delivers dream finish to Club America after World Cup fiasco |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/721973/2018/12/18/edson-alvarez-club-america-liga-mx-mexico-el-tri/ |access-date=2025-11-01 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On 23 February 2019, Álvarez made his 100th competitive appearance for América in the team's 3–0 victory over [[Lobos BUAP]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Edson Álvarez llegó a 100 partidos oficiales con América |trans-title=Edson Álvarez reached 100 official matches with America |language=es |url=https://www.telemundodeportes.com/liga-mx/edson-alvarez-llego-100-partidos-oficiales-con-america |website=telemundodeportes.com |publisher=Telemundo |date=23 February 2019 |access-date=23 February 2019}}</ref>

===Ajax===
[[File:GAE - Ajax - 52788526413.jpg|thumb|Álvarez (right) tackling against [[Go Ahead Eagles]] in 2023]]
On 19 July 2019, Dutch club [[AFC Ajax]] announced an agreement with Club América for the signing of Álvarez on a five-year contract, subject to a medical, for a reported fee of US$17&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|last=Valentine |first=Ben |title=Ajax complete $17m signing of versatile Mexico star Alvarez |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/ajax-complete-17m-signing-of-versatile-mexico-star-alvarez/hdlym7xyzhv414vc74sjhj9pm |website=Goal (website) |access-date=19 July 2019}}</ref> He passed his medical and was officially presented on 22 July, being handed the number 4 shirt which had been vacated following the departure of [[Matthijs de Ligt]]. The club announced an official transfer sum of €15&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Transfer completed: Edson Álvarez is now Ajacied! |work=Ajax English |url=https://english.ajax.nl/streams/ajax-now/transfer-completed-edson-alvarez-is-now-ajacied-.htm |publisher=[[AFC Ajax]] |access-date=22 July 2019}}</ref> On 17 August, Álvarez made his competitive debut for Ajax as a 74th minute substitute in the team's 4–1 [[Eredivisie|league]] win over [[VVV-Venlo]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Ajax brings 3 points back to Amsterdam |url=https://english.ajax.nl/streams/ajax-now/ajax-brings-3-points-back-to-amsterdam-.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200920005111/https://english.ajax.nl/streams/ajax-now/ajax-brings-3-points-back-to-amsterdam-.htm |archive-date=2020-09-20 |access-date=2025-11-01 |work=Ajax English |language=en-gb}}</ref> On 29 August, Álvarez scored his first goal in his first start against [[APOEL F.C.|APOEL]] in the second-leg of the [[2019–20 UEFA Champions League qualifying phase and play-off round#Play-off round|UEFA Champions League play-off round]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2019-08-28 |title=Mexico national team news: Edson Alvarez scores first Ajax goal in Champions League playoff |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/edson-alvarez-scores-first-ajax-goal-in-champions-league-playoff/47dkdz5c4ygz1tz8q22ykkrhe |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=www.goal.com |language=en-US}}</ref> On 17 September, Álvarez scored the second goal in the 3–0 Champions League group stage victory over [[Lille OSC|Lille]], becoming the first Mexican player to score on his Champions League debut.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ajax v Lille Match Report, 9/17/19, UEFA Champions League |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/match/ajax-v-lille/report/6gwdth6s62a4zgei83d3uh5yi |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200830204049/https://www.goal.com/en-us/match/ajax-v-lille/report/6gwdth6s62a4zgei83d3uh5yi |archive-date=2020-08-30 |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=www.goal.com |language=en}}</ref>

On 21 March 2021, Álvarez scored his first [[Eredivisie]] goal for [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] in a 5–0 victory over [[ADO Den Haag]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=2021-03-21 |title=Ajax ease to win over ADO Den Haag - Football Oranje |url=http://www.football-oranje.com/ajax-ease-to-win-over-ado-den-haag/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250429115149/http://www.football-oranje.com/ajax-ease-to-win-over-ado-den-haag/ |archive-date=2025-04-29 |access-date=2025-11-01 |work=Football Oranje |language=en-US}}</ref> On 18 April, in the [[2021 KNVB Cup Final|Dutch Cup final]] against [[SBV Vitesse|Vitesse]], he played the entirety of the match in a 2–1 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Neres’ stoppage-time goal seals Dutch Cup win |url=https://english.ajax.nl/articles/neres-stoppage-time-goal-seals-dutch-cup-win |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=english.ajax.nl |language=en-US}}</ref> At the end of his second season, he was nominated for the league Player of the Year Award.<ref>{{cite web|title=Edson Álvarez, nominado a jugador del año en Holanda|work=Marca|location=Spain |date=6 May 2021 |url=https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/futbol/mexicanos-mundo/2021/05/06/609430c5268e3e22478b45a6.html}}</ref>

On 27 October 2021, it was announced Álvarez had signed a contract extension with Ajax, keeping him with the club until 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Edson Álvarez verlengt contract bij Ajax |url=https://www.ajax.nl/artikelen/edson-alvarez-verlengt-contract-bij-ajax |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=www.ajax.nl |language=nl-NL}}</ref> On 30 April 2022 he was inducted into the club's ''[[Club van 100 (AFC Ajax)|Club van 100]]'', making his 100th appearance in a 3–0 league victory over [[PEC Zwolle]], becoming the 174th player in the history of the club to join the ranks.<ref>{{Cite web |title=How Edson Álvarez came to make his one hundredth appearance for the Ajax first team |url=https://english.ajax.nl/articles/how-edson-alvarez-came-to-make-his-one-hundredth-appearance-for-the-ajax-first-team |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=english.ajax.nl |language=en-US}}</ref>

===West Ham United===
[[File:Edson Álvarez 14092024.jpg|thumb|upright|Álvarez with [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in 2024]]
On 10 August 2023, English club [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] announced they had signed Álvarez on a five-year contract for a reported fee of £35&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |title=West Ham United sign Edson Álvarez {{!}} West Ham United F.C. |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/west-ham-united-sign-edson-alvarez |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=www.whufc.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2023-08-10 |title=Edson Alvarez: West Ham sign Ajax & Mexico midfielder for about £35m |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66463123 |access-date=2025-11-01 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He was handed the number 19 jersey.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Edson Álvarez: Why I’ve chosen the No19 shirt at West Ham United |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/edson-alvarez-why-ive-chosen-no19-shirt-west-ham-united |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=www.whufc.com |language=en}}</ref> He became the fourth Mexican player, after [[Guillermo Franco]], [[Pablo Barrera]], and [[Javier Hernández]], to represent West Ham United.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Seven things you need to know about West Ham United's new midfielder Edson Álvarez! |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/seven-things-you-need-know-about-west-ham-uniteds-new-midfielder-edson-alvarez |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=www.whufc.com |language=en}}</ref> He made his debut on 20 August, coming on as an 81st minute substitute for [[James Ward-Prowse]] in a 3–1 victory against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Emons |first1=Michael |title=West Ham 3–1 Chelsea |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66490161 |access-date=20 August 2023 |work=BBC Sport |date=20 August 2023}}</ref>

On 14 December 2023, Álvarez scored his first goal for West Ham, scoring against [[SC Freiburg]] in a 2–0 victory in the [[2023-24 UEFA Europa League group stage|Europa League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jurejko |first=Jonathan |title=West Ham 2–0 Freiburg: Mohammed Kudus and Edson Alvarez goals send Hammers into last 16 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67708087 |access-date=15 December 2023 |work=BBC Sport |date=14 December 2023}}</ref> On 2 March 2024, in a 3–1 win against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] at [[Goodison Park]], Álvarez scored his first Premier league goal collecting a pass from [[Jarrod Bowen]] in the 5th minute of added-time.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Everton v West Ham United {{!}} 2023/2024 {{!}} Premier League {{!}} Overview |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/match/2367800 |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=www.premierleague.com |language=en}}</ref>

====Loan to Fenerbahçe====
On 23 August 2025, Álvarez joined [[Süper Lig]] club [[Fenerbahçe S.K. (football)|Fenerbahçe]] on a season-long loan with option to buy.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Edson Álvarez joins Fenerbahçe SK on loan {{!}} West Ham United F.C. |url=https://www.whufc.com/news/edson-alvarez-joins-fenerbahce-sk-loan |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=www.whufc.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Transfer Bilgilendirme |url=https://fenerbahce.org/haberler/futbol/2025/8/transfer-bilgilendirme-tr |access-date=22 August 2025 |publisher=Fenerbahçe SK |date=22 August 2023 |language=tr}}</ref> He became the second Mexican player after [[Diego Reyes]], to represent Fenerbahçe. On 31 August 2025, he made his league debut with the team in a 3–1 away victory over [[Gençlerbirliği S.K.|Gençlerbirliği]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Fenerbahçe SK|url=https://fenerbahce.org/haberler/futbol/2025/8/genclerbirligi-1-3-fenerbahce|title=Gençlerbirliği 1-3 Fenerbahçe |date=31 August 2025|access-date=31 August 2025|language=tr}}</ref> On 2 October 2025, he made his continental debut for the club against [[OGC Nice]] in 2–1 league stage win in the [[2025–26 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://fenerbahce.org/haberler/futbol/2025/10/fenerbahce-2-1-ogc-nice |title= Fenerbahçe 2-1 OGC Nice  |publisher=Fenerbahçe S.K. |language=tr |date=2 October 2025 }}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
Álvarez was called up to the [[Mexico national under-20 football team|under-20]] team camp<ref>{{Cite web |title=Página Oficial de la Selección Nacional de México |trans-title=Official Page of the Mexico National Team |url=http://miseleccion.mx/convocatoria-de-la-seleccion-nacional-de-mexico-sub-20/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241204200250/http://miseleccion.mx/convocatoria-de-la-seleccion-nacional-de-mexico-sub-20/ |archive-date=2024-12-04 |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=miseleccion.mx |language=es-MX}}</ref> preparing for the [[2017 CONCACAF U-20 Championship]] en route to the [[2017 FIFA U-20 World Cup]]. He was included in the tournament's best XI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.concacaf.com/article/tsg-announces-cu20-best-xi-awards-2|title=TSG announces CU20 Best XI, Awards|publisher=CONCACAF.com|date=8 March 2017|access-date=10 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312051624/http://www.concacaf.com/article/tsg-announces-cu20-best-xi-awards-2|archive-date=12 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Álvarez was included in the World Cup under-20 squad, and scored the winning goal in Mexico's 3–2 win over Group B minnows [[Vanuatu national under-20 football team|Vanuatu]].

===Senior===
[[File:Edson Álvarez Mexico 2018.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Álvarez prior to the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] match against [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]]]]
On 30 January 2017, Álvarez received his first call up to the [[Mexico national football team|senior national team]] for a friendly against [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Zacarias |first=Mariana |title=Edson Álvarez se dice 'en shock' por la noticia del Tri |trans-title=Edson Álvarez says he is 'in shock' over the news of the Tri |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/2017/01/30/edson-alvarez-se-dice-en-shock-por-la-noticia-del-tri |access-date=30 January 2017 |website=Medio Tiempo |language=es}}</ref> He made his senior debut on 8 February against Iceland, replacing [[Jesús Molina]] in the 60th minute.<ref>{{cite web |date=9 February 2017 |title=Juan Carlos Osorio debutó a Edson Álvarez y Luis Reyes |trans-title=Juan Carlos Osorio debuted Edson Álvarez and Luis Reyes |url=https://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/mexico/nota/_/id/2970196/juan-carlos-osorio-debuto-a-edson-alvarez-y-luis-reyes |access-date=9 February 2017 |website=ESPN Deportes |language=es}}</ref> Along with [[Alejandro Mayorga]], he was cited to be a supporting practice squad player with the [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup|Confederations Cup]] team.<ref>{{cite web |title=Edson Álvarez y Alejandro Mayorga, 'invitados' de Osorio a Confederaciones |trans-title=Edson Álvarez and Alejandro Mayorga, Osorio's 'invitees' to the Confederations Cup |url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/2017/06/09/edson-alvarez-y-alejandro-mayorga-invitados-de-osorio-a-confederaciones |access-date=19 June 2017 |website=Medio Tiempo |language=es}}</ref> He was called up to the [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]], making him the youngest player on the squad. The roster was largely composed of alternate players, as the primary squad was in Russia competing in the Confederations Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.am.com.mx/2017/06/07/leon/deportes/elias-en-la-lista-preliminar-de-copa-oro-360107|title=Elías en la lista preliminar de Copa Oro|trans-title=Elías in the preliminary list of the Gold Cup|language=es|website=am.com|publisher=Periódico am|date=7 June 2017|access-date=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607174658/https://www.am.com.mx/2017/06/07/leon/deportes/elias-en-la-lista-preliminar-de-copa-oro-360107|archive-date=7 June 2017}}</ref> On 17 July, in the last game of the group stage against [[Curaçao national football team|Curaçao]], Álvarez scored his first goal for the national team in their 2–0 win, becoming the youngest Mexican player to score a goal in a Gold Cup tournament at 19 years old.<ref>{{cite web |title=Édson Álvarez, el mexicano más joven en convertir un gol en la Copa Oro |trans-title=Édson Álvarez, the youngest Mexican to score a goal in the Gold Cup |url=https://www.univision.com/deportes/futbol/copa-oro/edson-alvarez-el-mexicano-mas-joven-en-convertir-un-gol-en-la-copa-oro-video |access-date=18 July 2017 |website=Univision Deportes |language=es}}</ref>

In May 2018, Álvarez was named to Mexico's preliminary 28-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2018-06-04 |title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad - Final 23-man lists {{!}} Goal.com UK |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists-when-will-they-be-announced/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=www.goal.com |language=en-GB}}</ref> He was the youngest player on the list.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2018-06-04 |title=Mexico World Cup roster: Get to know Chicharito, Chucky Lozano and all the players called by Juan Carlos Osorio {{!}} Goal.com US |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/lists/get-to-know-hernandez-lozano--mexicos-world-cup-roster/ap4jr4lgpkj21f6893xm4wx58 |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=www.goal.com |language=en-US}}</ref> He was ultimately included in the final 23-man roster revealed on 4 June.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Página Oficial de la Selección Nacional de México |url=https://miseleccion.mx/convocatoria-la-seleccion-nacional-mexico-13/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250114000910/https://miseleccion.mx/convocatoria-la-seleccion-nacional-mexico-13/ |archive-date=2025-01-14 |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=miseleccion.mx |language=es-MX}}</ref> He appeared in all of Mexico's group stage matches; in Mexico's final group match against [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]], Álvarez started at right-back and scored an own goal at the 74th minute when the ball deflected off his left thigh in Mexico's 3–0 loss.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sweden v. Mexico |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/match/300331548/#match-liveblog|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612214518/https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/match/300331548/#match-liveblog|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 June 2018|publisher=FIFA|date=27 June 2018|access-date=18 September 2018}}</ref> He also started in the round-of-16 defeat to [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].

In May 2019, Álvarez was included in [[Gerardo Martino]]'s provisional [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]] roster.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tinajero |first=Antonio |date=2019-05-15 |title=S8 |url=https://s8-s8.com/ |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=FMF State Of Mind |language=en-US}}</ref> In a friendly match against [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]], he suffered an apparent knee injury<ref>{{cite web |last=Arnold |first=Jon |date=5 June 2019 |title=Alvarez injury in Venezuela friendly puts focus on Martino's provisional roster error |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/alvarez-injury-in-venezuela-friendly-puts-focus-on-martinos/k2xp4ra2lmfh1sl6r58keglir |access-date=2025-11-01 |work=Goal (website)}}</ref> but was revealed to only be a scare.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2019-06-06 |title=Mexico national team Edson Alvarez injury update: Midfielder says knee injury 'just a scare' {{!}} Goal.com US |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/mexico-midfielder-alvarez-says-injury-only-a-scare/1iotvtiqkj68710g1bybod3izc |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=www.goal.com |language=en-US}}</ref> He was included in the final list for the competition.<ref>{{cite web |last=Diaz |first=Rafael |date=5 June 2019 |title=Mexico unveil final Gold Cup roster; Edson Alvarez doubtful |url=https://www.fmfstateofmind.com/2019/6/5/18654884/mexico-unveil-final-gold-cup-roster-edson-alvarez-doubtful |access-date=2025-11-01 |publisher=Fmfstateofmind.com}}</ref> Álvarez appeared as a starter in five matches, including the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup Final|final]], as Mexico would go on to win the tournament.<ref name="auto">{{cite magazine |last=Straus |first=Brian |date=7 July 2019 |title=Mexico Turns Tide, Wins Gold Cup Title Again vs. Wasteful USMNT |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2019/07/07/mexico-usa-gold-cup-title-dos-santos-pizarro-pulisic-berhalter |access-date=2025-11-01 |magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]]}}</ref>

In October 2022, Álvarez was named in Mexico's preliminary 31-man [[Mexico national football team|squad]] for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]], and in November, was ultimately included in the final 26-man roster.<ref>{{cite web |last=Moro |first=Omar |date=14 November 2022 |title=Lista de convocados de la Selección Mexicana al Mundial de Qatar 2022 |url=https://www.tvazteca.com/aztecadeportes/lista-oficial-convocados-seleccion-mexicana-mundial-qatar-2022 |access-date=2025-11-01 |work=Tvazteca.com |language=Spanish}}</ref> Álvarez played in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup Group C|group stage]] draw against [[Poland national football team|Poland]]<ref>{{Cite news |date=2022-11-21 |title=World Cup 2022: Mexico 0-0 Poland: Robert Lewandowski misses penalty in World Cup opener |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63631782 |access-date=2025-11-01 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> as well as the win against [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=2022-11-29 |title=World Cup 2022: Saudi Arabia 1-2 Mexico - Gerardo Martino's side out on goal difference |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63725315 |access-date=2025-11-01 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 6 July 2025, he scored the winning goal in the [[2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup final]] in the 2–1 victory over the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] and was awarded the [[CONCACAF Gold Cup awards#Best player|Golden Ball]] award, signifying the best player of the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-03-11 |title=Game Details |url=https://www.concacaf.com/en/gold-cup/game-details/ |access-date=2025-11-01 |website=Gold Cup |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Concacaf Gold Cup awards: Edson Alvarez named Player of the Tournament |url=https://www.foxsports.com/stories/soccer/concacaf-gold-cup-awards-edson-alvarez-named-player-tournament |date=2025-07-06 |access-date=2025-07-07 |website=[[Fox Sports]]}}</ref>

